TY  - JOUR
T1  - Optimal Forecasting Incentives
AU  - Osband, Kent
Y1  - 1989/10/01
PY  - 1989
DA  - 1989/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261644
DO  - 10.1086/261644
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1091
EP  - 1112
VL  - 97
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - An agent of unknown expertise is requested to forecast the mean of an uncertain outcome. The agent can refine forecasts at a constant marginal cost per unit precision, but neither cost nor precision can be verified by the planner. The problem is to induce both truthful revelation and an appropriate degree of learning so as to minimize the expected sum of direct planning losses and agent payments. Optimal contracts are derived with and without self-screening of expertise and with and without competition between agents. Self-screening tends to be much less valuable than competition.
AB  - An agent of unknown expertise is requested to forecast the mean of an uncertain outcome. The agent can refine forecasts at a constant marginal cost per unit precision, but neither cost nor precision can be verified by the planner. The problem is to induce both truthful revelation and an appropriate degree of learning so as to minimize the expected sum of direct planning losses and agent payments. Optimal contracts are derived with and without self-screening of expertise and with and without competition between agents. Self-screening tends to be much less valuable than competition.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261644
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261644
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Transportation, State Marketing, and the Taxation of the Agricultural Hinterland
AU  - Gersovitz, Mark
Y1  - 1989/10/01
PY  - 1989
DA  - 1989/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261645
DO  - 10.1086/261645
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1113
EP  - 1137
VL  - 97
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - In raising revenues, governments of poor countries affect farm gate prices for export crops. Because agriculture is dispersed, interventions have spatial effects, leading to an integrated analysis of taxation, marketing, and transportation. Policies to be used singly or together include land, export, and transportation taxes/subsidies and variants of state marketing, in which only government procures crops. An export tax and a transport subsidy may be optimal. With state marketing, important aspects of buying depots are numbers, locations, spatial pattern of prices paid, and movement of output toward or away from the ultimate market. These policies also affect transport investment strategies.
AB  - In raising revenues, governments of poor countries affect farm gate prices for export crops. Because agriculture is dispersed, interventions have spatial effects, leading to an integrated analysis of taxation, marketing, and transportation. Policies to be used singly or together include land, export, and transportation taxes/subsidies and variants of state marketing, in which only government procures crops. An export tax and a transport subsidy may be optimal. With state marketing, important aspects of buying depots are numbers, locations, spatial pattern of prices paid, and movement of output toward or away from the ultimate market. These policies also affect transport investment strategies.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261645
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261645
Y2  - 2024/03/22
